==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from
<ets>ticket</ets>.]</ety> <def>Credit; trust; <as>as, to buy on, or
upon, <ex>tick</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go on trust, or
credit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give tick; to trust.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tike</ets>, <ets>teke</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>teek</ets>, G. <ets>zecke</ets>. Cf. <er>Tike</er> a
tick.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any one of numerous
species of large parasitic mites which attach themselves to, and suck
the blood of, cattle, dogs, and many other animals. When filled with
blood they become ovate, much swollen, and usually livid red in color.
Some of the species often attach themselves to the human body. The young
are active and have at first but six legs.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any
one of several species of dipterous insects having a flattened and
usually wingless body, as the bird ticks (see under <er>Bird</er>) and
sheep tick (see under <er>Sheep</er>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tick bean</b></col>, <cd>a small bean used for feeding
horses and other animals.</cd> -- <col><b>Tick trefoil</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a name given to many plants of the leguminous
genus <gen>Desmodium</gen>, which have trifoliate leaves, and joined
pods roughened with minute hooked hairs by which the joints adhere to
clothing and to the fleece of sheep.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>techa</ets>,
<ets>teca</ets>, L. <ets>theca</ets> case, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to put. See
<er>Thesis</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The cover, or case, of a bed,
mattress, etc., which contains the straw, feathers, hair, or other
filling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Ticking. See <er>Ticking</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ticked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ticking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably of imitative origin;
cf. D. <ets>tikken</ets>, LG. <ets>ticken</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make a small or repeating noise by beating or otherwise, as a
watch does; to beat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike gently; to pat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand not <qex>ticking</qex> and toying at the branches.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A quick, audible beat, as
of a clock.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any small mark intended to direct attention to
something, or to serve as a check.</def> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The whinchat; -- so called from
its note.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Death tick</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Deathwatch</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Tick
<hw>Tick</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To check off by means of a tick or
any small mark; to score.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When I had got all my responsibilities down upon my list, I
compared each with the bill and <qex>ticked</qex> it off.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ticken</ent>⟦br⟧
